SIMPLE: mop
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Mop
<hw>Mop</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Mope</er>.]</ety>
<def>A made-up face; a grimace.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧What <xex>mops</xex> and
mowes it makes!⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Beau. & Fl.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mop</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Mop
<hw>Mop</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To make a wry mouth.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mop</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Mop
<hw>Mop</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[CF. W. <ets>mop</ets>,
<ets>mopa</ets>, Ir. <ets>moipal</ets>, Gael. <ets>moibeal</ets>,
<ets>moibean</ets>; or OF. <ets>mappe</ets> a napkin (see <er>Map</er>,
<er>Napkin</er>).]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An implement for washing
floors, or the like, made of a piece of cloth, or a collection of
thrums, or coarse yarn, fastened to a handle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A fair where servants are hired.</def> <mark>[Prov.
Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The young of any animal; also, a young girl; a
moppet.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark> <rj><au>Halliwell.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mop head</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>The end of a mop, to
which the thrums or rags are fastened</cd>. <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>A clamp for
holding the thrums or rags of a mop.</cd> <mark>[U.S.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mop</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Mop
<hw>Mop</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Mopped</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Mopping</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To rub or wipe with a mop, or as
with a mop; <as>as, to <ex>mop</ex> a floor; to <ex>mop</ex> one's face
with a handkerchief.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mopboard</ent>⟦br⟧
